Hi Mark,

I'd say that this is quite a broken approach to using `union`. There is nothing defined as `ipv6Address` anywhere, so I'm not clear how one could actually figure out that `ipv6Address` means `inet:ipv6-address`. PyangBind also doesn't actually know that this is the relevant `typedef` either - as you can see, it has already expanded this out into a single `RestrictedClass`. 

Today - the code does not generate any kind of static types - e.g., `Enum` classes for enumerations, or `typedef` statements. This is at the expense of generating them each time they are needed (as basically PyangBind makes all types immutable). The only way that I can think that you would be able to do this is:

 * For every union type find the corresponding entries in the `class_map` dictionary.
 * Make the `base` argument to `YANGDynClass` take a dictionary rather than a list - this would need to be done for unions and anything else that can appear in that list with >1 entry too. This dictionary would e of the form` {'typename': <definition>}`.
 * When setting the value, store the key of the dictionary in some new variable in the `YANGBaseClass` meta-class, such that you can access it at serialisation time.
 *  You would also need to store all the keys of all the dictionaries that you had [0] such that you could set these to `None`.
 * Implement a custom `serialiser` class that now looks specifically at `union` types and does this serialisation.

This is quite a lot of work for something that's not  part of any standard, and quite broken. It seems to me that the API should use a `container` here rather than a `union` since it's trying to include both leaves. Programatically, it does not seem trivial to generically map from the name of the `typedef` into these names; plus it's not clear to me what one does in this case:

```yang
leaf example {
   type union {
     type int8 {
        range "1..2";
     }
     type int8 {
       range "4..8";
    }
  }
}
```

I'm going to (rudely) close this issue as `wontfix`; I don't expect many folks to do this - as it's in clear violation of the specification of a `union` type.

Feel free to re-open if there are further questions.

Cheers,
r.

[0]: In the case that you have a union that includes another union then you'd need to do something like:

```python
def find_all_keys(d, current_keys=[]):
  current_keys.expand(d.keys())
  for k, v in d.iteritems():
    if isinstance(v, dict):
      find_all_keys(v, current_keys=current_keys)
 return current_keys
```

This would find all the keys in nested dictionaries, as well as the top level dictionary.

