@waynebloss at the moment the folks working on Watchman don't run it on Windows for any real purpose.  We're anticipating that this will change in the future, which is why we've added support and have CI configured and so on.  Until that changes and we've seen what really happens to the system outside of our integration test suite, we feel that it would be disingenuous to label it more than alpha or perhaps beta.

Watchman provides both a real-time file change subscription mechanism (echoing what the native OS facilities provide, but in a cross-platform way) and functionality to query the view of the filesystem without talking to the filesystem.  The latter part of this may sound strange, but when you are dealing with a very large directory tree, the act of looking at a "cold" portion of it can block for a non-trivial amount of time.

Whether watchman is necessary depends on your needs.

After #317 is merged, this will be a working example:

```python
import re
import types
import spectate
from traitlets import *

class Eventful(TraitType):

    def __init__(self, trait_type, *active_methods, **kwargs):
        if active_methods is None:
            raise ValueError("Eventful instances must have active methods")
        self.trait_type = trait_type
        self.watched_type = spectate.watched_type(
            trait_type.klass.__name__,
            trait_type.klass, *active_methods)
        super(Eventful, self).__init__(**kwargs)

    def _validate(self, obj, value):
        return self.watched_type(self.trait_type._validate(obj, value))


# not thread safe
class TraitValueEventHandler(ObserveHandler):

    def __init__(self, type, on):
        if on is None or not re.match(r'^[^\.]*\.[^\.]*$', on):
            raise ValueError("Provide a trait's dotted method - e.g. 'trait.method'")
        trait, method = on.split('.')
        self.trait_names = (trait,)
        self.method = method
        self.type = type

    def _init_call(self, func):
        def register_instance_callbacks(inst, change):
            out = func(inst)
            before, after = (out if
                isinstance(out, tuple)
                else (out, None))
            change.new.spectator_callback(self.method,
                before=before, after=after)
        self.func = register_instance_callbacks
        return self


def event(type='change', on=None):
    return TraitValueEventHandler(type, on)
```

```python
class HasEvents(HasTraits):
    
    elist = Eventful(List(), '__setitem__')
    
    @event(on='elist.__setitem__')
    def elist_set_callbacks(self):
